This topic describes how to delete the AWS resources associated with an <%= vars.ops_manager %> deployment.

## <a id="overview"></a> Overview

When you deploy <%= vars.ops_manager %> to Amazon Web Services (AWS), you provision a set of resources.
You can use the AWS console to remove an installation of all components,
but retain the objects in your bucket for a future deployment.

## <a id="prerequisites"></a> Prerequisites

Before you can delete resources from AWS, you must have an account with access to your AWS Management Console.

For more information, see [AWS Management Console](https://aws.amazon.com/console/) in the AWS documentation.

## <a id="delete"></a> Delete Resources from AWS

To delete the resources associated with <%= vars.ops_manager %> from AWS:

1. Log into the AWS Management Console.
1. Navigate to the EC2 Dashboard.
  1. Select **Instances** from the menu on the left side.
      1. Select the Ops Manager instance from the list.
      1. Select **Actions** to open the drop down menu.
      1. Under **Instance State**, select **Terminate**.
      1. A modal will appear prompting you to confirm the termination of the instances. Click **Yes, Terminate** to confirm.
  1. Select **Load Balancers** from the menu on the left side.
      1. Select the web, SSH, and TCP load balancers from the list.
      1. Select **Actions** to open the drop down menu.
      1. To delete all load balancers, select **Delete**.
      1. A modal will appear prompting you to confirm the deletion of the load balancers. Click **Yes, Delete** to confirm.
1. From the AWS Console, select **RDS**.
  1. Select **Instances** from the menu on the left side.
      1. Select **Instance Actions** to open the drop down menu.
      1. To delete all RDS instances, select **Delete**.
  1. The **Delete DB Instance** pane appears.
      1. Select **Create final Snapshot** from the drop down menu.
      1. To delete the database instance, click **Delete**.
1. From the AWS Console, select **S3**.
  1. Select **Buckets** from the menu on the left side.
  1. For each bucket created, do the following:
      1. Select the bucket.
      1. Click **Delete**.
      1. You will be taken to a page to confirm the deletion of the bucket. Enter the name of the bucket into the confirmation text field, then click **Delete bucket**.
1. From the AWS Console, select **VPC**.
  1. Select **NAT gateways** from the menu on the left side.
      1. Select the NAT gateway you created for your installation.
      1. Select **Actions** to open the drop down menu.
      1. To delete the NAT gateway, select **Delete NAT gateway**.
      1. A modal will appear prompting you to confirm the deletion of the NAT gateway. Enter `delete` into the confirmation text field, then click **Delete**.
  1. Select **Your VPCs** from the menu on the left side.
      1. Select the VPC you created for your installation.
      1. Select **Actions** to open the drop down menu.
      1. To delete the VPCs, select **Delete VPC**.
      1. A modal will appear prompting you to confirm the deletion of the VPC. Enter `delete` into the confirmation text field, then click **Delete**.
